info.title: project44 Ocean Container Track & Trace API
info.description:
This [RESTful HTTP API](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Representational_state_transfer) allows to track and trace ocean freight containers.
It completely covers the lifecycle of a container, including
  * current status and position of a container,
  * past route with timestamps of important events and
  * scheduled routing and estimated timeline for the remaining transport.

Once you subscribe to a container, our systems constantly monitor
and analyze related information from various sources.
This allows you to retrieve updated container information
via this API or even be informed by pushed messages.
Throughout this API, the lifecycle of a container, its status and progress
are modeled by _milestones_ at _key sites_ - the most important ones depicted in the figure below.
Currently, our model supports up to four transshipments.
During ocean legs and especially regarding port arrivals or departures,
our systems actually track the container vessels using a satellite and land-based AIS receiver network.

![Image](data:image/png;base64,)

In order to simplify communication of this model, the following short codes for key sites and milestones can be used.

* Empty Pickup Depot
  * __CEP__ --- container empty to shipper
* Origin
  * __CPS__ --- container pickup at shipper
* Port of Loading (__POL__)
  * __CGI__ --- container arrival at first POL (gate-in)
  * __CLL__ --- container loaded at first POL
  * __VDL__ --- vessel departure from first POL
* Transhipment Port (__T/S__)
  * __VATx__ --- vessel arrival at T/S port
  * __CDTx__ --- container discharge at T/S port
  * __CLTx__ --- container loaded at T/S port
  * __VDTx__ --- vessel departure from T/S port
* Port of Discharge (__POD__)
  * __VAD__ --- vessel arrival at final POD
  * __CDD__ --- container discharge at final POD
  * __CGO__ --- container departure from final POD (gate-out)
* Last Inland Facility (__LIF__)
  * __CIF__ --- container arrival at LIF (gate-in)
  * __COF__ --- container departure from LIF (gate-out)
* Delivery (__DLV__)
  * __CDC__ --- container delivery to consignee
* Empty Return Depot
  * __CER__ --- container empty return to depot

# Basic Concepts and Workflow

This API builds on two central concepts. A _Container_ represents
a specific container on its journey from origin to destination.
But using this API, you do not subscribe containers for tracking directly.
Instead, you submit _Subscriptions_, representing a related batch of containers.
This approach allows to intuitively manage batches referred by _Bill of Lading_ or _Booking_ numbers,
potentially including several containers.
Together, these concepts enable the following basic workflow.


1. Your systems subscribe to containers - preferably by _bill of lading_, but also by _booking_ or _container_ numbers.
2. Our tracking systems start monitoring the containers in the background.
3. Your systems regularly check for update events or are informed via pushed event messages.
4. When our tracking systems detect completion of the containers, this is signaled by appropriate events and status.

Completed containers will no longer be monitored or updated,
but are kept in the system for analytics.
To achieve the same effect before completion, subscriptions can also be explicitly _archived_.
Finally, subscriptions can be _cancelled_ to even exclude them from analytics.

# Multi-User Accounts

The (opt-in) multi-user account feature allows to assign each subscription to one account,
so only users having access to its account will be able to access a subscription and its containers.
Using an appropriate user and account setup, you can divide all containers tracked by your organization
into logical groups, for example representing
  * departments
  * customers
  * markets

Once this feature is enabled, every API request must be associated with an account to identify the correct scope.
Otherwise, the API will respond with a corresponding error status and message.
In most cases however, the account membership of a requesting user can be resolved automatically.
But for users having access to multiple accounts, the request's query parameter `account` must unambiguously identify the account.
In addition, newly created subscriptions must be assigned to an account using the `account` property in the request's body.

If this feature is not enabled for your organization, subscriptions are not assigned to accounts.
When it gets enabled, all existing subscriptions will automatically be associated with the first account created.
There will be at least one _master user_ with administrative rights for your organization.
While master users are responsible for ongoing account and tag configuration,
initial user and account membership will be configured by our support team.
Please get in touch with us for details on how to get started.

# Tagging

The (opt-in) tagging feature allows to attach custom labels to both subscriptions and containers.
Combined with tag-based search, this enables powerful and flexible workflows
to support even sophisticated use cases.
In a sense, tagging complements multi-user accounts in structuring your tracking activities.

Tags can be attached and removed throughout the whole lifecycle of subscriptions and containers.
But keep in mind that tag management - creating, modifying and deleting tags themselves -
requires master user privileges. Moreover, availability of this opt-in feature depends on your setup.
Please contact us, we are happy to support you in leveraging this feature to the full extent.

# Access Control through Tags

Besides the _Multi-User Accounts_ feature described above there is another, more flexible method available for controlling access to subscriptions and containers. The access control feature (opt-in) is mutual exclusive with multi-user accounts, so you can only use one of both modes, and it implicitly requires the tagging feature to be enabled.

As with multi-user accounts, using an appropriate user and access control tags setup you can group all subscriptions of your organization into arbitrary subdivisions. But beyond that common functionality, with this feature it is possible for different users to access overlapping groups of subscriptions and to have more fine-grained control over the visibility of shipments.

This feature utilizes the existing tagging system and allows controlling access by assigning specially marked tags to both users **and** subscriptions or containers. Access to the requested (list of) object(s) is granted when the requesting user shares at least one access control tag with the tags assigned to the object(s).

**Note:**
> We refer to this default mode of operation - at least one - as _ANY_ mode, and plan to provide other modes in future versions.

The following prerequisites and restrictions apply to make tag-based access control work:
  * As with multi-user accounts, initial setup of the specially marked tags will be done by our customer success team in close consultation with your organization. This includes assigning access control tags to users of your organization, in the desired combinations.
  * For a user to access subscriptions or containers tagged with a certain tag, the user needs to have that same tag assigned.
  * Accordingly, to make new subscriptions accessible for users, the subscriptions **must have** at least one access control tag assigned. Therefore, when creating subscriptions, at least one of these tags has to be referenced in the `tag_ids` field of the corresponding POST request body. Otherwise subscription creation will be rejected by the validation logic. (This restriction is limited to subscription level and does not apply to creation of containers when using the "On-hold" mechanism.)
  * A regular user will be able to choose from the set of access control tags that has been configured and assigned to that user beforehand.
  * Once assigned to a newly created subscription, a regular user is not allowed to annul or change the access control tag(s).
  * There can be one or more users with administrative rights for access control (access control administrators) which are allowed to remove and re-assign the specially marked tags arbitrarily from / to subscriptions after creation, still with the restriction that at least one of these tags has to remain.
  * These access control administrators will in addition be able to choose from **all** available access control tags from your organization, not limited to the scope of their own configuration.
  * To retrieve the list of available access control tags, limited to the scope as configured for regular users, or all for access control administrators, you can use the _Tags_ endpoint. Said tags are marked as `is_access_control: true` in the corresponding GET response.

If this feature gets enabled and a multi-user account setup existed and was used by then, it will be ignored for all future requests and account information will not be considered for access control.

Please reach out to our customer success team if you would like to activate and configure this feature for your organization.

# Concepts and Endpoints

The following UML class diagram depicts the relationships between the six major concepts of this API.
  * A subscription consists of one or more containers.
  * Subscriptions and containers can be tagged flexibly.
  * A container may be affected by multiple incident warnings.
  * In multi-user account setups, all subscriptions must be associated with exactly one account.
  * Users can have access to multiple accounts and access to an account can be granted to many users.

![Image](data:image/png;base64,)

These concepts correspond to the endpoints provided by this API
  * `/subscriptions/` Subscribe containers and retrieve subscription status
  * `/shipments/` Retrieve status of containers
  * `/accounts/` Manage multi-user accounts
  * `/tags/` Manage tags
  * `/events/` Retrieve a list of recent container events
  * `/carriers/` Retrieve a list of supported carriers and their codes
  * `/incidents/` Retrieve a list of incident warnings

# Web Application

In addition to this API, we offer a web application providing many advanced features like
searching and filtering of subscriptions and containers, exception alerts and reporting dashboards.
The user and account setup, subscription assignments and tagging feature all work seamlessly
across this API and the web app. Please contact us for more information.

# Event Push Service

For performance and scalability reasons, we highly recommend to use our Event Push Service instead of repeatedly polling this API.
This service will notify your servers (via HTTP POST) about any events detected on active subscriptions and containers.
This documentation contains all information necessary to implement support for pushed events in your server systems.
Please get in touch with us to discuss details and configure the Event Push Service for you.

# Status Page and E-Mail Notification

In case of an unexpected downtime, an inevitable scheduled
maintenance time or a service degradation,
we communicate the latter centrally through our system status information platform at
[https://status.project44.com/](https://status.project44.com/).
We strive to give you, as soon as possible, any necessary background information
on what services are affected to what extend and when a solution may be expected
in order to facilitate your planning. We strongly recommend to subscribe
your e-mail address to the status update service.

# Support

If you have questions or need help, dont hesitate to send an e-mail to
[support.americas@project44.com](mailto:support.americas@project44.com) or [support.europe@project44.com](mailto:support.europe@project44.com).
We are here to support you in every way we can, and take our pride in you being able
to integrate with our API as smoothly as possible!

# Notes and Remarks

## API rate limit

Generally, a rate limit ensures the scalability and stability of a product API by throttling incoming requests after a limit was
reached.

Every endpoint in this API has a rate limit of **5 requests per second** based on authenticated user (Basic or Token authentication).

When a throttle is triggered by performing a sixth request within a second, the API will respond with the proper HTTP 429 code. Then no further requests will succeed until one second has passed.

Your application should consider this concept and handle it accordingly by distributing requests over time. That can be achieved by either directly limiting the requests done per second or by incorporating the error code 429 into your retry mechanism, so throttled requests will be performed at a later time.

## Trailing Slashes

The trailing slashes are important for this API to work correctly in all situations.
If you omit trailing slashes you might experience unexpected and weird behaviour.
Hence, we recommend to _always_ include trailing slashes, i.e.
```/subscriptions/``` instead of ```/subscriptions```.

## Pagination

On some endpoints the number of resulting items can be quite high.
By default, the API uses a pagination mechanism and only returns the first page of 200 items.
You can control pagination via the `page` and `page_size` query parameters as specified below.
To indicate the page navigation options in a response, a 'Link' header will provide links
to the previous and next page.

`Link: <url-of-next-page; rel='next'>, <url-of-previous-page; rel='prev'>`

## Date vs. Date-time Format

Depending on the settings of the authorized user performing the API request
all milestone related time fields of container shipments are given either in `date-time` format
or in `date` format.<br>
Note that the underlying data of `*_planned_initial` and
`*_planned_last` fields often may not have a date-time
resolution and therefore the midday time "12:00:00" is given.

## Evolution of this API

We may add, change or remove undocumented fields, schemas, enumerated values and events
at any time in preparation of new features and capabilities.
In order to maximize stability of your integration with this API and minimize
your maintenance efforts, please follow some basic guidelines.

Please make sure, that _your code safely ignores additional, undocumented fields, schemas, enumerated values and events_.
Any usage of undocumented fields, schemas, enumerated values or events is at your own risk.
Once a field, schema, enumerated value or event is documented in this specification, it is safe for use - it will not be altered or removed.
This API will not introduce breaking changes, all changes are backwards compatible.

## On-hold Mechanism

For B/L or booking number subscriptions, the `on_hold` property can be used for fine-grained control over tracked containers.
By default, our systems detect and automatically create _all_ containers of a subscription shortly after its creation.

To provide initial data for containers _before detection_ (i.e. tags, descriptive name),
set the `on_hold` property to `true` when creating the subscription. This results in the container detection being suspended.
While the subscription is on hold, you can create containers and provide initial data by POSTing to `/shipments/`.
It is strictly required to reference the subscription by id in each container creation request body.
The subscription's `container_filter` property will be auto-filled with corresponding container numbers.
Hence, only those containers explicitly added will be tracked by the subscription.

Finally, update the subscription's `on_hold` property to `false` to start its initializing procedure.
Note that subscriptions `on_hold` longer than a week will be automatically started (i.e. `on_hold` set to `false`).
The whole `on_hold` mechanism only works upon creation of a subscription before it transitions from `new` to `active` state.

## Status of Subscriptions

A subscription is attributed with a status field that reflects whether updates to its containers are received. These are namely:

* `new`
* `active`
* `completed`
* `archived`
* `invalid`
* `cancelled`

`new` is the initial status for subscriptions. These are ready to receive container updates.

An `active` subscription received at least once data for its containers and in general will continue to do so until its journey is completed.

Once all containers in a subscription have their lifecycle completed the subscription is `completed` too.
Completed subscriptions can be manually `archived`. Doing so will remove them from active monitoring, but they will be still considered for statistics.

A `cancelled` subscription will receive no further updates and is also excluded from any statistics.

Subscriptions may get into the status `invalid` for different kinds of reasons. These are

* The `request_key` is not valid and therefore no updates can be received.
* The subscriptions `request_type` is `c_id` and no update from the carrier is received for 30 days.
* The subscriptions `request_type` is `b_id`, `m_bl` or `h_bl` and no update from the carrier is received for 90 days.

Not every status can transition into another is possible, since that won't reflect any real workflow. The following transitions are possible:

* `new`  `active`
* `new`  `completed`
* `new`  `invalid`
* `new`  `cancelled`
* `active`  `completed`
* `active`  `cancelled`
* `completed`  `archived`
* `completed`  `cancelled`


## Validation of Subscriptions

Before a subscription is created, the submitted tracking number is validated to conform to these rules
  * Container numbers feature 4 uppercase letters followed by 7 digits (see [ISO 6346](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/ISO_6346))
  * B/L and booking numbers are assumed to feature 7 to 20 alphanumeric characters

We recommend to properly validate numbers in your application according to the same rules before submitting subscriptions.

After this initial rough validation, our systems perform more robust checks to identify _suspicious keys_, i.e. tracking numbers for which data might not be available. Subscriptions for such numbers will be accepted and while marked by `suspicious_key: true` in the response, they will _not_ be treated special.

Furthermore, creation of duplicate subscriptions is actively prevented based on the submitted tracking number, and a corresponding error response will be issued in case the submitted data does not pass validation, according to the following policy:
  * For all three request types, there must not be more than one subscriptions with statuses `new`/`active`.
  * Also pertaining to all types, if there already are 3 subscriptions with identical `request_key` in status `cancelled`, adding another one is inhibited.
  * This applies to B/L and booking number types (`m_bl`, `b_id` & `h_bl`) in status `invalid`, too (i. e. max. 3 `invalid` subscriptions for these two request types).
  * For both types `m_bl`, `b_id` and `h_bl`, any existing subscriptions in statuses `completed` or `archived` also prevent creation of another subscription with the same tracking number.

**Note:**
> If an `owner_internal_id` is present, it is incorporated into detecting duplicate subscriptions, which means there can be two or more active subscriptions with identical tracking number (`request_key`) for the same `request_type` when different values for `owner_internal_id` are given respectively. That is, you have to be aware that by submitting unique `owner_internal_id`s, you would effectively circumvent this duplicate prevention logic.

In case the _Access Control through Tags_ feature is enabled, the ID of at least one access control tag must be present in the `tag_ids` field of the POST body for subscription creation. Please refer to the corresponding section of this document for details.

## Branded Status Pages

Subscriptions and shipments in CTT support the generation of branded status pages.
These can be used to view the object in a web browser without logging into the track
and trace platform. They are cryptographically signed and hence unguessable. For technical
reasons, the URLs of these pages might change between subsequent API calls. This does not
imply that previous URLs are invalidated.

You can also generate these URLs yourself by creating a key in the [service center](https://capi.ocean-insights.com/sc/public_link_key_management/).
These symmetric keys are used for generating HMAC SHA-256 based JWTs that can be used to
authenticate URLs for subscriptions and shipments:

<dl>
  <dt>Shipment</dt><dd><tt>https://ctt.ocean-insights.com/#/shipment/:shipment-id:/?share=:token:</tt></dd>
  <dt>Subscription</dt><dd><tt>https://ctt.ocean-insights.com/#/subscription/:subscription-id:/?share=:token:</tt></dd>
</dl>

### Token Generation

Tokens that authenticate branded status pages are generated as [JWT (JSON web tokens)](https://jwt.io),
a web standard with wide programming language support. When generating a key, the CTT service center will
present you with a JWK encoded representation of the key.
This key will only be shown to you once, so make sure that you save a copy before dismissing the form.

The JWK contains the base64-url encoded secret used to sign tokens and a hexadecimal key ID. You use the
key id to generate the <em>header</em> for the token, as such:

<pre>
{
  "typ": "JWT",
  "alg": "HS256",
  "kid": "0cf267a54f7e417fb4073126f28975ea"
}
</pre>

The token <em>payload</em> will be formed by concatenating the numeric ID of the shipment or token with the prefixes <tt>shp:</tt>
or <tt>sub:</tt> respectively and setting those as the subject (<tt>sub</tt>) of the token. In addition, the token is
required to contain a random <tt>nonce</tt>:

<pre>
{
  "sub": "shp:12345678",
  "nonce": "BT3-ZdiPdWgHT3hUq9wICiXMbzcXiVpq8xA7mE"
}
</pre>

The final token is formed by concatenating the base64-url encoded header, payload, and signature, separated by a <tt>.</tt> and appended to the URL as the `share` parameter:

<pre>:header:.:payload:.:signature:</pre>

project44 can provide code samples for .NET, Java, and Python that demonstrate how to implement
status page link generation using common frameworks.

**Note:**
> Availability of this feature depends on your setup. Please contact our sales representative if you
> are interested.

## Error Logging

In case of errors, this API provides detailed error descriptions in the response bodies.
Especially for `400 - Bad Request` generic status code errors,
logging this information is indespensible for debugging.
Therefore, we recommend to log all responses of `4xx` and `5xx` status codes _including response bodies_!


## Abbreviations

Throughout this documentation, the following abbreviations are used frequently:
  * _T/S: Transshipment_
  * _POL: Port of Loading_
  * _POD: Port of Discharge_
  * _B/L: Bill of Lading_

post.description:
Add new containers to be tracked by creating a subscription.
(Usage of the 'oicode' carrier code is recommended to identify carriers.
You can request all supported codes on the `/carriers/` endpoint.
The subscription is rejected if required parameters are missing,
the tracking number is invalid or an identical subscription
already exists for this request key.)

---
Once the subscription is created, it is returned in the response body.
Its 'suspicious_key' flag indicates if data might be unavailable for this tracking number.
Moreover, the subscription will initially have an empty 'containershipments' list.
Its containers will be detected shortly afterwards when the subscription transitions
from the 'new' to the 'active' state.

**Note:**
  > For some carriers, it is required to append a valid container number as suffix
  > in the `request_key` property in format [request_key]-[container_number] when creating a subscription
  > (example: "request_key": "AIS0141508-CMAU3086614").
  > Otherwise, no data can be retrieved for that carrier and the subscription will invalidate.
  > Affected carriers have a note in the remarks column in the following table
  > [Carrier Coverage and Data Quality](https://capi.ocean-insights.com/sc/quality_report/)

  * 17 => 'number of T/S changed (rerouting)' - the number of transshipments has changed
  * 20 => 'location update' - daily report of the container's position
  * 24 => 'ETD discrepancy at POL' - the contracted ETD at POL is not matched by the reported ETD'
  * 25 => 'ETA discrepancy at POD' - the contracted ETA at POD is not matched by the reported ETA
  * 26 => 'ETA discrepancy at place of delivery' - the contracted delivery ETA is not matched by the reported ETA
  * 30 => 'Release state changed' - the hold/release state by the carrier or customs changed
  * 31 => 'Container available' - the container is available for pickup by the consignee
  * 40 => 'Arrival predicted' - a prediction regarding arrival of the container at the POD or a T/S port has been made or changed
  * 100 => 'shipment initialized' - carrier has been successfully retrieved for the first time
  * 101 => 'shipment invalid' - deprecated (moved to subscription level)
  * 102 => 'shipment expired' - the container is expired (reason given in 'details' field)
  * 103 => 'shipment re-initialized' - the containing subscription and all its containers have been re-initialized
  * 104 => 'shipment AIS data regenerated' - AIS data for this container had to be flushed and re-generated (very rare case)

tags.name: OI LOCODE Set
tags.description:
We have found that LOCODEs are used inconsistently across carriers and across our different customers. There is an official UN LOCODE definition list, however at a closer look it leaves room for doubts and ambiguities.

project44 makes sure that in our data, incoming LOCODEs (e.g., from different carriers) are mapped consistently to one LOCODE set ("OI LOCODE set"). However, we are unable to match the different LOCODE set variants of all our customers. Hence, we recommend you create a mapping from the OI LOCODE set to "your" specific LOCODE set.

We aim to keep the OI LOCODE set stable over time, even if updates to the official UN LOCODE definition are published, so that your mapping will remain intact. In case we need to make adjustments to the OI LOCODE set in the future, we will announce such well ahead of time.

tags.name: Event Push
tags.description:
We highly recommend using our Event Push Service instead of repeated polling.

  > __ATTENTION: Concerning Event Push, the client-server roles are inversed: You have to provide an HTTP server,
  > which our systems access as an HTTP client to push the event messages via HTTP POST requests.__
  > This reference specifies the API endpoint and payload your server implementation
  > has to support to process pushed events.

After activation and configuration, our service will notify you about any events detected on your active subscriptions and containers. You have to provide a server handling HTTP POST requests submitting the pushed events. In order to best secure your push event integration, combining HTTPS and Basic Auth is recommended. Additionally, the event messages will contain a security token for authentication. Only if the security token matches, you will know that the message comes from the correct sender. A secret hash salt will be agreed between you and us. This hash salt is used in creating a hash of the message timestamp.

    ts = convert_to_unix_timestamp(t)
    hashvalue = concatenate_strings(str(ts),hashsalt)
    hashdigest = sha1(hashvalue).hexdigest()
    if (hashdigest == json_payload['security_token']):
      print "Valid"
